=====================================
Basic HTML Guide for Absolute Beginners
=====================================

1. What is HTML?
-----------------
HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language. It is used to create and structure content on the web. HTML uses "tags" to define elements.

A very basic HTML document looks like this:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>My First Web Page</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <!-- Content goes here -->
  </body>
</html>


2. Displaying Text
-------------------
Use heading tags <h1> to <h6> for headings, and <p> for paragraphs.

Example:

<h1>Main Heading</h1>
<h2>Subheading</h2>
<p>This is a paragraph of text.</p>


3. Adding Line Breaks and Horizontal Lines
------------------------------------------
Use <br> to break lines, and <hr> to draw a horizontal line.

<p>This is line one.<br>This is line two.</p>
<hr>


4. Formatting Text
-------------------
You can make text bold, italic, or underlined:

<p><b>Bold</b> <i>Italic</i> <u>Underline</u></p>


5. Creating Buttons
--------------------
Buttons are created using the <button> tag.

Example:

<button>Click Me</button>

You can add actions to them with JavaScript (see below).


6. Adding Links
----------------
Use the <a> tag to create hyperlinks:

<a href="https://www.google.com">Go to Google</a>


7. Adding Images
-----------------
Images are added with the <img> tag. Include the "src" (source) and "alt" (alternative text).

<img src="image.jpg" alt="A description of the image" width="300">


8. Adding JavaScript Functions
-------------------------------
JavaScript lets you add interactivity to your page.

Example: a button that shows a message:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Button Example</title>
    <script>
      function sayHello() {
        alert("Hello, world!");
      }
    </script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <button onclick="sayHello()">Click Me!</button>
  </body>
</html>


9. Input Fields and Forms
--------------------------
Forms let users enter data.

Example:

<form>
  Name: <input type="text" name="username"><br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>


10. Saving and Viewing Your HTML File
--------------------------------------
1. Open Notepad or any text editor.
2. Paste your HTML code.
3. Save the file as: yourfilename.html
4. Double-click the file to open it in your web browser.

NOTE: You must use .html extension (NOT .txt) to make it viewable in a browser!

--------------------------------------
End of Basic HTML Guide
--------------------------------------

You can now start experimenting by combining these elements!
